7373348294212209950.voice_to_text: as a safety concern I just wanna point out you have to really be careful when using a product outside it's intended to use to dupe another product. and duping a product is a bit more complicated than just looking at the first few ingredients *listed like 70% isopropyl alcohol is not a dupe for setting spray. for one there are two different types of alcohol. rubbing alcohol is isopropyl alcohol and alcohol in setting sprays is usually the type we drink just denatured it a little bit so you don't drink it but it's also not the first ingredient and not the only ingredient because it's not the alcohol itself that sets your makeup. the alcohol is just a carrier or solvent for the actual ingredients that set the makeup called fixatives. As the alcohol evaporates, the fixative forms a film on the face to lock makeup into place same way Hairspray works. That’s why Hairspray is an affordable dupe for setting sprays. another example would be using Gorilla Snot as a eyeshadow. Just because a product is safe for one area of the body, doesn't mean it's safe for all areas of the body because beyond shampoos, hair products typically are not tested to be eye safe, so just be careful when using some of these dupes.

7369389718087339310.voice_to_text: About this 27 year old woman that dropped all of her children off to CPS a week before mother. Okay, I'm gonna give my opinion about this whole story. If you haven't already heard about it, go ahead and watch the whole first video. This is coming from a mom who's had a child at a very, very young age. And also, I had a mother who did not raise me, and my grandmother raised me. But we are gonna start off with this whole situation. Is this horrible? Those poor kids are suffering no matter what. Like, I could not imagine already going through a horrible and stressful situation, uh, with your mother dropping off at CPS, but then having it also go viral on TikTok. And it's gonna be like, they're gonna grow up and they're gonna see all this, and already they're probably seeing so much about it. So I know she's mentally unfit, and she just pretty much just had a mental breakdown over all this. But still, I don't think she'll realize she did the right thing in a way. But also, if she were to, like, fix up her life and try and get her kids back, it is gonna be very hard. Now, I'm not saying she shouldn't get her kids back. I just think it's gonna take too much time to rebuild her relationship with her children and earn their trust back. Because when you still think about it, what she did, She could have done privately. She could have not done all those lives and all those videos. And then maybe I would see more potential of her possibly getting her children back. But right now or anytime soon, I don't think she should. It's still better though that she picked to drop them off, because I could imagine possibly what their home life was going to be like if she already was that overwhelmed, that mentally stressed out, and she just couldn't handle anything anymore. And then they just feel like probably they're not wanted. Like it was it. And then like, who knows how much longer it would have just taken for CPS to come into the situation anyways.

7368209308485422379.voice_to_text: You can only do silicone and silicone or you can only do water based with water based are completely wrong. I try to tell people this all the time. Whoever started this whole water based water based silicone silicone is like the biggest marketing scheme that's currently happening in like the makeup community. Number one. Most of your products have both water and silicone in it anyways, so if it can't mix on your face, why can't it mix in the product and be okay? Also, if you're moisturizing or using sunscreen, it's probably water based too, not silicone based. So why can you put silicone primer and foundation on that and it doesn't peel? Why does it only matter for the primer and the foundation if you find something spilling on your face? There could be a million different reasons why, but I'll usually take all my makeup off and exfoliate my face and then reapply my skincare and it'll end up looking fine for the most part. I use water based primer and silicone in this and foundation and it looks good. So moral of the story just don't believe everything you see on TikTok and don't fall into schemes where now you feel like you have to label all of your different products or go out and buy different one.

7371463872248597793.video_description: This one’s for the magazine collectors, the fashion hoarders and those constantly working on their vision boards.  Do you think Suede could exist today? Could it be print or would it be online only? #makeup #fashion #fashionhistory #beauty #blackfashion #fashiontiktok #magazine #fashioncommentary #beautytok
7371463872248597793.voice_to_text: What if I told you that the best black fashion magazine ever created was a publication that hardly anyone got to see? Suede magazine was a joint venture between essence magazine and Time, Inc. And it launched in 2004 with a focus on luxurious fashion for women of color. However, it did not last very long. The first cover, which came out in September 2,004, featured Alicia Keys, the second cover saw Eve, the third was Zoe Saldana, and the fourth and final cover featured Tyra Banks. As well as these glamorous, well known names on the covers, the brands throughout were luxurious Chanel, YSL, Valentino, Elie, Saab, and throughout the magazine there were these beautiful illustrations and detailed editorials crafted by creative director Richard Christensen. The rest of the team included Suzanne Boyd as editor, Ying Chu as beauty director, Ian Hilton as editor at large, and Agnes Kamak as fashion, market, news and trends director. I was recently reminded of suede magazine's existence when I chatted to Andrea Lewis, the creator of the Netflix documentary series The Black Beauty Effect. It was supposed to be Essence's Millennial Girl magazine. It was four girl millennial millennial girls that were young at the time. The black millennial girl deserves see herself on this really luxe level, deserves to see herself on this really creative level. So we're gonna create this magazine. At the time, suede magazine was described as a multicultural woman's fashion glossy, and others described it as a Black take on Harper's Bazaar. Even Time, Inc's editor in chief at the time, Norman Perlstein, said that suede was, quote, one of the freshest, most exciting magazines to come out in years. So what happened? At the time, there were rumors that essence was intimidated by the sheer sales that suede was making. But I think a far more likely explanation would be that the sales were low. It's really hard to launch a new title, and advertisers were promised a guaranteed circulation of 250,000. However, essence never revealed the actual new stand sales, given the fact they already had 40 people on the team. I just think money ran out, and it is a huge shame. Before I go, let me read you the manifesto that went out in the very first issue of Suede. Style is in our DNA, and we, the multi culti urbanistas, stand at a new intersection of street and chic. Our dial is tuned to the catwalk and the corner. We are fashion crazy. We come from the culture on the come up and use fashion to amplify who we are. We revel in the entire spectrum of black beauty and love the skin we're in. Feel it. Let me know. Do you know suede?

7369720694508195114.voice_to_text: You need to throw these away immediately. If you are using makeup wipes to take off your makeup, you need to stop, and let me tell you why. Disclaimer I am a licensed esthetician, so I know what I'm talking about. So not only do these not remove your makeup completely, it also disrupts your acid mantle, which is the protective layer of your skin, which keeps all the good things in and the bad things out. When you're wiping the skin over and over and over, that is considered tugging, and when you tug at the skin, it causes premature aging. Also disrupt your pH balance of your skin, and they can also cause micro tears in your skin. And the naked eye can't spot micro tears, but if you look under a microscope, you can see tiny tears in your skin. A majority of makeup wipes do contain alcohol, which is very stripping to the skin's barrier, and you will not be able to maintain a healthy barrier if you're gonna continue to put alcohol on your face. Especially if you're using this on your eyes to remove eye makeup, that is one of the worst places that you can use this on. The skin around the eye area is the most delicate and thinnest. When you're tugging and wiping and irritating, it most definitely will be causing premature wrinkles. Instead of this, use something like this. Micellar water is one of the best ways to remove makeup. It is very gentle and it's not gonna irritate the skin. My favorite right now is this Fenty Skin Jelly Oil Makeup Melting Cleanser. This works so well at removing the makeup and it's very, very gentle. As you can see, I used half the bottle already. One of my most favourite makeup cleansing balms to ever exist is this one by versed. You can get this at target. So bye bye to this, hello to this.

7367126852135062826.video_description: Text DONATE to 43428 to help Earthjustice protect wildlife from seismic air gun suveys. #seismic #whale #dolphins #ecotok #oilandgas #climatechange
7367126852135062826.voice_to_text: The oil and gas industry is profiting by setting off explosions in one of the world's biological hotspots. This is called seismic airgun surveying, and it's used to search the ocean for oil. A single ship can blast every 10 seconds, 24 hours a day, seven days a week, for months on end. The air guns are like mini cannons and the blast can exceed 235 decibels, which is hundreds of times more intense than a jet engine. A marine mammal in the vicinity would be deafened. Most of this is happening in the Gulf of Mexico, home to some of the world's most endangered species. The blasts can inflict permanent, even fatal, hearing damage on whales, dolphins, even affect the plankton that's the foundation of the ocean food web. The sound waves can be heard across the entire Gulf. This near constant level of noise can mask vital calls that marine mammals depend on to survive. The Biden administration has a chance to reign in this harmful activity. Unfortunately, it issued a new rule that would still allow extensive seismic testing in the Gulf of Mexico. The environmental law organization Earthjustice is asking the administration to change course and correct the rule, so that it protects Gulf wildlife from seismic air gun surveys. If you'd like to support this work please text DONATE to 43438

7364131349596212526.voice_to_text: Every foundation in the world, from the lightest to the deepest, is made with at least these five pigments or a combination of white, yellow, red, black, and even green. With these five pigments, you can make almost any skin colour and undertone that exists. I have a lot of experience creating foundation. I started over 35 years ago with my first foundation palette at MAC Cosmetics up until today with Mauve Beauty Blurring Ceramide Cream Foundation with over 36 shades and four undertones. I even helped Crayola develop their colors of the world crayons so every child could find their shade in a crayon box. Here is one of the charts we use to help develop the undertones at MOB. You can see how the undertones go from pink to neutral to gold and then olive. Depending on the depth and the undertone, it will determine which combination of the five pigments we use. I would call myself a medium neutral to golden undertone. And I'll show you how we use the five pigments to get to eye shape. So we've got the white in the middle, and I'm gonna add some yellow. I'm gonna need some red as well, but you can see that that's a little bit too pink, so I'm gonna have to dull it down a little bit. And that's what the black is used for. The black kind of dulls the color down a little bit, but because I have a little bit of Olive undertone. I'm just gonna add a touch of green. Just a touch. And that's how you need the five pigments to get to my depth and my undertone. In conclusion, foundation shades are nuanced. Everyone has a unique undertone from the lightest shade to the deepest shade. Which is why using a combination of the five pigments are essential in order to create the unique undertones needed.

7341185331141594410.video_description: Best bagels ever. Recipe below  Pre-Ferment 2 ½ cups bread flour   ½ tsp instant yeast  1 ½ cups warm water (110 °F)  Dough 2 cups  bread flour  ½ tsp instant yeast  1 ½ tsp coarse salt  1 tsp light honey  2 tsp apple cider vinegar  Water bath 10 cups of water ½ cup Dark Beer 1 tsp *Baked* baking soda  3 tbsp dark brown sugar   Instructions - Pre-ferment.  To a medium bowl, add bread flour and yeast.  Mix until combined then add your water. Let that sit at room temp for 2 hours. Right on top of that add your ½ tsp yeast, salt, honey and vinegar. Stir until combined then add in half of your bread flour. (only 1 cup) Add flour until you have a kneadable dough ball. Knead that until you have a smooth, supple dough. Divide your dough into 6 equal balls, shape each one then cover with damp towels for 1 hour. Grab a heavy baking sheet that will fit in your fridge, put a piece of parchment paper on top then add a light layer of coarse cornmeal. To shape your bagels, gently flour the tops of them.  Flour your thumb then make a hole straight through the middle. Twist them around your fingers til you get a 1 inch hole. Re-Dampen your towels, cover then refrigerate your bagels for 1 hour. To bake, heat your oven to 425°F. In the meantime add 10 cups of water to a pot then add *baked baking soda, your favorite dark beer and brown sugar. *Simply bake ½ a cup of baking soda 30 mins at 350F then let it cool. Bring to a boil then add as many bagels as you can fit without them overlapping.  Boil them for 1 minute per side. (longer for chewier bagels, shorter for less chewy) Remove them with a slotted spoon to a baking tray. Immediately brush with egg wash (1 egg white + 1 tsp water) then sprinkle with whatever toppings you like. Transfer into your preheated oven for 5 minutes. After 5 minutes, rotate the tray then bake for 16 more minutes (flip halfway through) Take them out and let them cool on a wire rack. You can wait a few mins and eat them fresh or wait a couple hours until they are cooled. Make this recipe and let me know what ya think… Appreciate the support!!! 🙏🏽🤘🔥 #bagels #bageltok #easyrecipe
